Let $n$ be a positive integer. I conjectured that the following inequality is true
\begin{equation}
n^{n+1} \leq (n+1)^{n} \sqrt[n]{n!} .
\end{equation}
Anyhow I could neither prove nor disprove it. I could only check, by using Stirling's Formula, that the ratio of the right and left members tends to 1 as $n \rightarrow \infty$. Any help is welcome.

Recall that Thomae's function (also called Popcorn function) $f\colon\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ is defined as 
$$
f(x) = \begin{cases}
\frac{1}{q} & \text{ if } x=\frac{p}{q} \neq 0 \text{ is rational, } \gcd(p,q)=1 \text{ and } q> 0\\
0 &\text{ otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$
In particular, it is a standard exercise to show that $f$ is continuous at every irrational, and discontinuous at every rational. Find a sequence of continuous functions $(f_n)_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ that converges pointwise to $f$ on $[0,1]$.

